President Trump signed a presidential memorandum to improve access to water in California, Oregon, and Washington. He criticized the current water management practices and federal regulations that have hindered water infrastructure projects in the American West. The President directed Secretary Zinke and Secretary Wilbur Ross to streamline approvals for federal water infrastructure and eliminate unnecessary burdens. He also mentioned the importance of resolving issues blocking the completion of water projects in California's Central Valley and other areas. The President emphasized the potential economic benefits and job creation that would result from improving water access. He also addressed questions about the investigation into the killing of journalist Jamal Khashoggi and the issue of election interference. Regarding the caravan of migrants heading towards the US, President Trump expressed his intention to call up the military if necessary to prevent their entry into the country.